The whole emphasis in pronouncing this sentence lies upon this word, which discovers Chaerea to have accomplishments above his rank, who, though he appeared to be no more than a slave, yet was equally skilled in those polite arts, as if he had been born and educated a citizen. It was the practice sometimes among the ancients to educate slaves with care, either that they might sell for the greater price, or be the more serviceable to their masters. See Hor. Epist. ii. 2. 6.
